{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "To attach a temperature sensor to a BeagleBone Black, we have followed the"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "tutorial"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "created by Simon Monk for the AdaFruit Learning System. The electronics are very simple and connect the three pins of a TMP36 temperature sensor to an analogue input on the BeagleBone Black. The software side involves"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "installing  and using an AdaFruit library"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "to read the value and we end up running a Python program similar to this:"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "import Adafruit_BBIO.ADC as ADC\nimport time\n\nsensor_pin = 'P9_40'\n\nADC.setup()\n\nwhile True:\n   reading = ADC.read(sensor_pin)\n   millivolts = reading * 1800  # 1.8V reference = 1800 mV\n   temp_c = (millivolts - 500) / 10\n   print('mv=%.2f C=%.2f' % (millivolts, temp_c)\n   time.sleep(1)"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "So now we have a source of temperature data. Now we can MQTT enable this program. Our first stop is the Eclipse Paho project where MQTT client libraries for various languages have been assembled. There you can find the Paho Python library, but as it is yet to be formally packaged and released, we will need to build it. To build it for the BeagleBone Black\u2019s Angstrom Linux distribution we first need to download the source code using git:"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "git clone https://github.com/eclipse/paho.mqtt.python.git org.eclipse.paho.mqtt.python.git"}
