{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "Formatting the values to two decimal places for tidiness. This gives us our complete program:"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "import time\nimport Adafruit_BBIO.ADC as ADC\nimport paho.mqtt.client as mqtt\n\nsensor_pin = 'P9_40'\nADC.setup()\n\nmqttc = mqtt.Client()\nmqttc.connect(\"m2m.eclipse.org\", 1883, 60)\nmqttc.loop_start()\n\nwhile True:\n  reading = ADC.read(sensor_pin)\n  millivolts = reading * 1800  # 1.8V reference = 1800 mV\n  temp_c = (millivolts - 500) / 10\n  print('mv=%.2f C=%.2f' % (millivolts, temp_c))\n  mqttc.publish(\"bbbexample/tmp36/mv\",\"%.2f\" % millivolts);\n  mqttc.publish(\"bbbexample/tmp36/c\",\"%.2f\" % temp_c);\n  time.sleep(1)"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "And running that should publish values to the Eclipse sandbox every second. To check this is happening without writing a client, we can make use of one feature of the Eclipse M2M sandbox, the"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "Eclipse MQTT Bridge"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "(at eclipse.mqttbridge.com), which presents the contents of a sandbox in easily consumable web formats. By using the curl utility, it is possible to obtain the value from the last message passed through the broker like so:"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "# curl http://eclipse.mqttbridge.com/bbbexample/tmp36/c\n19.10#"}
{"link": "http://www.eclipse.org/paho/articles/talkingsmall/", "text": "We shall return to the BeagleBone Black and the Python client later; the next stop for us is creating a client that will use that temperature data."}
