{"link": "https://www.eclipse.org/paho/clients/cpp/", "text": "These C++ clients connect to a broker using a TCP/IP connection using Posix or Windows networking, threading and memory allocation calls. They cannot be used with other networking APIs.  For that, look at the Embdedded C/C++ client."}
{"link": "https://www.eclipse.org/paho/clients/cpp/", "text": "Here is a simple example of publishing with the C++ client synchronous API:"}
{"link": "https://www.eclipse.org/paho/clients/cpp/", "text": "int main(int argc, char* argv[])\n{\n    const std::string TOPIC { \"hello\" };\n    const std::string PAYLOAD1 { \"Hello World!\" };\n\n    const char* PAYLOAD2 = \"Hi there!\";\n\n    // Create a client\n\n    mqtt::client cli(ADDRESS, CLIENT_ID);\n\n    mqtt::connect_options connOpts;\n    connOpts.set_keep_alive_interval(20);\n    connOpts.set_clean_session(true);\n\n    try {\n        // Connect to the client\n\n        cli.connect(connOpts);\n\n        // Publish using a message pointer.\n\n        auto msg = mqtt::make_message(TOPIC, PAYLOAD1);\n        msg->set_qos(QOS);\n\n        cli.publish(msg);\n\n        // Now try with itemized publish.\n\n        cli.publish(TOPIC, PAYLOAD2, strlen(PAYLOAD2), 0, false);\n\n        // Disconnect\n\n        cli.disconnect();\n    }\n    catch (const mqtt::exception& exc) {\n        std::cerr << \"Error: \" << exc.what() << \" [\"\n            << exc.get_reason_code() << \"]\" << std::endl;\n        return 1;\n    }\n\n    return 0;\n}"}
