{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "\u2013 or subscribe with an array of filters and an optional array of QoS values to go with them. The QoS setting is, by the way, a maximum so that if you have subscribed with a QoS of 1, messages published with a QoS of 0 or 1 will be delivered at that QoS and messages published with a QoS of 2 will be delivered at a QoS of 1."}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "Once subscribed, messages will begin arriving at the"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "messageArrived()"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "callback method where the topic and"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "MqttMessage"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "are passed in as parameters. When in"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "messageArrived()"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": ", newly arriving messages will be queued up and the acknowledgement for the message being processed will not be sent till the callback has cleanly completed. If you have complex processing of the message to do, copy and queue the data in some other mechanism to avoid blocking the messaging system."}
