{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "Subscriptions are affected by the clean session flag used when establishing a connection. If a session has the clean setting set to false, the system should persist the subscriptions between sessions and shouldn\u2019t need to resubscribe. With the clean flag set to true, the client will have to resubscribe when reconnecting. When a client does subscribe to a topic, it will receive all the retained values that match the topic they are requesting, even if the subscription\u2019s topic query is in part or in whole intersecting with a previous subscription."}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "One important point to note is that we have, for simplicity, only covered the synchronous version of the API where every call to the MQTT API blocks and the only thing that comes through on its own schedule are inbound messages from subscriptions. This version of the API,"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "MqttClient"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": ", is a thin wrapper around the more powerful asynchronous version of the API,"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "MqttAsyncClient"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": ", where all calls do not block, giving their results either by the application monitoring a token which is returned by the call or by the completed action calling back to a class that implements an"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "IMqttActionListener"}
{"link": "https://www.infoq.com/articles/practical-mqtt-with-paho/", "text": "interface. When you progress further into developing MQTT-based applications, it is worth considering whether using the synchronous API or the asynchronous API is more appropriate for your case."}
