{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "2.2.3\r\nRemaining Length"}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "Position:"}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "starts at byte\r\n2."}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "The Remaining Length is the\r\nnumber of bytes remaining within the current packet, including data in the\r\nvariable header and the payload. The Remaining Length does not include the\r\nbytes used to encode the Remaining Length."}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "The Remaining Length is encoded\r\nusing a variable length encoding scheme which uses a single byte for values up\r\nto 127. Larger values are handled as follows. The least significant seven bits\r\nof each byte encode the data, and the most significant bit is used to indicate\r\nthat there are following bytes in the representation. Thus each byte encodes\r\n128 values and a \"continuation bit\". The maximum number of bytes in\r\nthe Remaining Length field is four."}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "Non normative\r\ncomment"}
{"link": "http://docs.oasis-open.org/mqtt/mqtt/v3.1.1/os/mqtt-v3.1.1-os.html", "text": "For example, the\r\nnumber 64 decimal is encoded as a single byte, decimal value 64, hexadecimal\r\n0x40. The number 321 decimal (= 65 + 2*128) is encoded as two bytes, least\r\nsignificant first. The first byte is 65+128 = 193. Note that the top bit is set\r\nto indicate at least one following byte. The second byte is 2."}
