{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "When you compare that to the old code, then you will notice that instead of an array, now a list is being used and the class name changed. Not too bad."}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Also, the way you create a new client instance with Milo 0.3.x is a bit different now:"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "OpcUaClientConfigBuilder cfg = new OpcUaClientConfigBuilder();\ncfg.setEndpoint(endpoints[0]); // please do better, and not only pick the first entry\n\nOpcUaClient client = OpcUaClient.create(cfg.build());\nclient.connect().get();"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Using the static"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "create"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "method instead of the constructor allows for a bit more processing, before the class instance is actually created. Also may this new method throw an exception now. Handling this in an async way isn\u2019t too hard when you are using Java 9+:"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "public static CompletableFuture<OpcUaClient> createClient(String uri) {\n  return DiscoveryClient\n    .getEndpoints(uri) // look up endpoints from remote\n    .thenCompose(endpoints -> {\n      try {\n        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(\n            OpcUaClient.create(buildConfiguration(endpoints)) // \"buildConfiguration\" should pick an endpoint\n        );\n      } catch (final UaException e) {\n        return CompletableFuture.failedFuture(e);\n      }\n    });\n}"}
