{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "This is the message generated by the JVM when running in debug mode, and it gives us the information that the port used is 5005."}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Now you can create a remote Java debugger. Even better, because the message has been recognized by the Eclipse Java development tools, you just need to click on the list associated with the message and Eclipse will magically create a remote Java debugger and connect it to your Quarkus application!"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "After clicking on the hyperlink, you will see nothing because the remote Java debugger has been launched in the background and it connected to your Quarkus application. However, you can check it if you switch to the"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Debug"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "perspective. To do that, open the"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Window -> Perspective -> Open Perspective -> Debug"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "menu and select the"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Debug"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "view. You should see something similar to:"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "As you can see, the debugger is connected to the Quarkus application. That means you can add breakpoints in your application source code and, next time you send a request, the Quarkus JVM will stop and the Eclipse IDE will step to the code in which you set a breakpoint."}
