{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "In addition the"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "specification"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "scope which is required by the Eclipse Intellectual Property Policy and EFSP, the"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "specification project"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "that owns and maintains the specification needs a"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "project scope"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": ". The project scope is, I think, pretty straightforward: a particular specification project defines and maintains a specification."}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "For example:"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "The Jakarta Batch project defines and maintains the Jakarta Batch specification and related artifacts."}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "Like the specification scope, the project scope should be aspirational. In this regard, the specification project is responsible for the particular specification in perpetuity. Further the related artifacts, like APIs and TCKs can be"}
{"link": "https://planeteclipse.org/planet/", "text": "in scope"}
